{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17507563","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17507563"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:54:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:54:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2640"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2640","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2640"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.17,0.06,0.2,0.52]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2640"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109305"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2640","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2640"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2640"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91669"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"3470"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3041"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3066"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3408"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31812"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109305","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109305"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 44-year-old man presents to his General Practitioner with a four day history of diarrhoea, starting the day after he returned from a holiday in Cambodia. He is passing about eight watery stools a day. There is no pus nor blood in the stool. He does not have any other symptoms, particularly no fever, vomiting or abdominal pain. Whilst on holiday he ate out at the local restaurants and from street stalls. He has not come into contact with anyone who had any gastrointestinal symptoms. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, his blood pressure is 110/70mmHg, pulse 100/min and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. The abdominal examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying cause of his diarrhoea?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Clostridioides difficile","Salmonella typhi","Shigella flexneri","Campylobacter jejuni","Enterotoxigenic Escherichia coli (ETEC)"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case describes travellers\u0027s diarrhoea in someone who has gastroenteritis symptoms after returning from a south-east asian country. Most causes of acute travellers\u0027 diarrhoea can be of bacterial, viral or parasitic origin and often a stool culture is required to identify the pathogen. However, sometimes typical features from the history can suggest a causative organism too. Watery stools in the absence of associated symptoms such as fever, abdominal pain or bloody stools is typical of an \u003Cstrong\u003EEnterotoxigenic \u003Cem\u003EEscherichia coli \u003C/em\u003E(ETEC)\u003C/strong\u003E infection whereas \u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ECampylobacter\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EShigella\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ESalmonella\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E infections often present with those associated symptoms. \u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EClostridioides difficile\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E is not a typical causative organism of traveller\u0027s diarrhoea and is often associated with prior antibiotic use.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Enterotoxigenic Escherichia coli (ETEC) is a common organism that causes traveller\u0027s diarrhoea which typically presents with watery diarrhoea."],"references":["Barrett J, Brown M. Diarrhoea in travellers. Medicine. 2018;46(1):24-29. Available at: https://www.bmj.com/content/353/bmj.i1937.long"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91669"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2640"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91669","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91669"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-19T19:28:53+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-19T19:28:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2640"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109305"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https:/